components.html:
Dear Respondent,

We invite you to participate in the following survey to assess the effectiveness and success of the 5-year Together for Wildlife Strategy three years into its implementation. This survey will provide valuable insights into the progress made towards achieving the goals and objectives of the strategy, the challenges and opportunities encountered along the way, inform improvements to implementation and set the beginning of the comprehensive review and updating process (Action 17).

Your feedback is critical to the success of this survey, as it will help us understand the perspectives and experiences of those directly involved in the implementation of the strategy. Your participation is entirely voluntary, and all responses will remain anonymous and confidential.

The objectives of this survey are to:

  1. Evaluate the progress made towards achieving the goals and objectives of the Together for Wildlife Strategy.
  2. Identify the challenges and opportunities encountered in implementing the strategy.
  3. Gather feedback on the effectiveness and success of the strategy from stakeholders and Ministry staff.
  4. Identify areas for improvement in the implementation of the strategy.
  5. Identify ways to improve how funding from the strategy is allocated, reviewed, and applied.

Your participation in this survey is greatly appreciated. We thank you in advance for sharing your thoughts and experiences with us. The survey should take approximately 10-15 minutes to complete, and your responses will be crucial in helping us improve the implementation of the Together for Wildlife strategy.

 

Thank you for your support.

 

Sincerely,

 

 Rodrigo Solis-Sosa, PhD, DVM (He/Him)

 Human Dimensions of Wildlife Specialist, Together for Wildlife

I acknowledge with respect the sqciya tmx (Katzie) and Slh Tmxw (St:lo) peoples whose traditional territory I live, learn and work.

components.title: Goal 1  All British Columbians have a voice in Stewardship
components.tooltip: Wildlife stewardship is a shared responsibility and requires that everyone have a voice. This strategy is the Provinces commitment to develop inclusive and cooperative governance structures and to make existing engagement processes more transparent and effective. We will build new relationships to ensure that we work in partnership with all British Columbians to improve outcomes for wildlife stewardship.

components.label: On a 1-5 scale, how would you rate our performance or achievement (progress) on the following aspects of the strategy?

questions.label: Establish a Ministers Wildlife Advisory Council (MWAC) with members from across British Columbia.
Create or expand existing Regional Wildlife Advisory Committees (RWAC) to represent a variety of perspectives and provide opportunities for collaboration to improve wildlife stewardship
Tailoring of RWACS to meet unique needs and priorities of each region
Increase opportunities for the public to learn about and engage on wildlife stewardship issues that are important to them

Update and expand wildlife and habitat communications, conduct province-wide surveys to better understand priority issues and opportunities, and hold public open houses in different areas of the province

components.label: If you are not completely satisfied with the performance of any of the actions within this Goal so far, please use the space below to let us know any suggestion that would improve its implementation

components.title: Goal 2  Data, information, and knowledge drive better decisions
components.tooltip: The right data, information, and knowledge are essential for successful wildlife stewardship. Acquiring and sharing the right data, information, and knowledge will require that our data and knowledge systems be modernized in collaboration with Indigenous governments, local governments, resource industries, stakeholders, non-government organizations, and the public.

components.label: On a 1-5 scale, how would you rate our performance or achievement (progress) on the following aspects of the strategy?

questions.label: Expand biological data and information gathering about species and habitat conservation across BC
Expand social data and information gathering about species and habitat conservation across BC
Expand economic data and information gathering about species and habitat conservation across BC
Support of priority research for wildlife stewardship through contributions to post-secondary institutions
Sharing of results from research supported by the Together for Wildlife strategy
Development of a community science framework to provide new opportunities for British Columbians to partner in wildlife stewardship data collection and monitoring
Ensuring that wildlife and habitat data are accessible to everyone, are reliable and integrated, including wildlife harvest statistics, wildlife inventory and monitoring data, and research findings
Completion of the ongoing Fish and Wildlife Data and Licensing Transformation project

components.label: If you are not completely satisfied with the performance of any of the actions within this Goal so far, please use the space below to let us know any suggestion that would improve its implementation
Panel
components.title: Goal 3 - Stewardship actions achieve tangible benefits for wildlife
components.tooltip: To improve wildlife stewardship, we need the right tools to deliver tangible, on-the-ground changes in a timely way. We need to ensure our existing toolswhether policies, legislation, financial mechanisms, land designations, or restoration and enhancement activitiesare effective in achieving the intended outcomes and, where needed, develop new tools, including legislation, policies, and procedures, to respond to our changing world

components.label: On a 1-5 scale, how would you rate our performance or achievement (progress) on the following aspects of the strategy?

questions.label: Establish clear, measurable objectives for wildlife stewardship that take into consideration the interactions among species
Draft a renewed approach for setting objectives and linking wildlife populations and habitat.
Implement broad engagement, by developing provincial stewardship frameworks and regional stewardship plans for priority species and populations.
The implementation of on-the-ground efforts for enhancing and restoring priority habitats such as wetlands and grasslands
The implementation of on-the-ground efforts for reducing wildlife mortality on highways and railways
The implementation of on-the-ground efforts for reducing wildlife conflicts with communities
The implementation of on-the-ground efforts for deactivating and reclaiming resource roads
The implementation of on-the-ground efforts for managing key threats to wildlife and habitats, including invasive species, interspecies interactions, and disease
Strategically leveraging other funding opportunities to maximize benefits for wildlife

Completion of a comprehensive review of land designations under the Land Act, Wildlife Act, Oil and Gas Activities Act, and Forest and Range Practices Act that contribute to conservation to ensure they effectively target the intended habitats
Make investments to manage existing Conservation Lands
Acquisition of new priority lands for wildlife stewardship

Leverage of funds acquired for the creation of additional investments, strengthening ties with Indigenous governments, conservation partners, resource industries, and stakeholders to secure better and manage Conservation Lands

Wildlife Act review, making recommendations to address priority issues, such as reconciliation with Indigenous peoples, determination of objectives, improved wildlife stewardship, effective and accessible service delivery, and dedicated funding.
Review existing and potential funding models and make recommendations to ensure sufficient, dedicated, long-term funding for wildlife and habitat stewardship

components.label: If you are not completely satisfied with the performance of any of the actions within this Goal so far, please use the space below to let us know any suggestion that would improve its implementation
Panel
components.title: Goal 5  Collaboration advances reconciliation with indigenous Governments
components.tooltip: Our Together for Wildlife strategy will create new opportunities to work collaboratively with Indigenous governments to effectively and efficiently deliver wildlife stewardship. We will know that our work together is successful when Indigenous rights are recognized by society as foundational to how the Province and Indigenous governments steward wildlife and when Indigenous peoples can meaningfully practise their traditions and customs.

components.label: On a 1-5 scale, how would you rate our performance or achievement (progress) on the following aspects of the strategy?

questions.label: Policy development and legislative proposals to advance co-management and shared decision-making with Indigenous governments

Jointly develop, along with the First NationsB.C. Wildlife and Habitat Conservation Forum, communication and extension materials to educate and inform British Columbians about the nature of Aboriginal rights and titles, modern and historical treaties, Indigenous worldviews, and Indigenous use of wildlife and wildlife stewardship approaches.
Incorporation of Indigenous knowledge into statutory and non-statutory wildlife stewardship decision-making through the collaborative development of policies and procedures
Policy development and legislative proposals to advance co-management and shared decision-making with Indigenous governments
Evaluation, in collaboration with participating Indigenous governments, of existing Guardian and compliance projects with a focus on wildlife and habitat stewardship
Support of current and creation of new Guardian and compliance programs locally implemented under Indigenous government's request
Investment in developing models and approaches for sharing wildlife and habitat data and information with Indigenous governments
Investment in capacity to ensure Indigenous governments can effectively and efficiently participate in all aspects of wildlife stewardship
Development of pilot initiatives to involve collectives of Indigenous governments to deliver trusted information to support shared stewardship

Support the operation of a formal First NationsB.C. Wildlife and Habitat Conservation Forum to provide one source of Indigenous perspectives on the development of policies and legislation that will support wildlife and habitat stewardship across provincial government programs and with Indigenous governments
